New York Evictions

New York City wish to conduct a study that aims to prevent people being evicted through understand possible related factors.You have been enlisted as a consultant and tasked to conduct an analysis of their data from 2020. You should use appropriate data processing and analysis methods to produce an overview report which summarises the patterns revealed in the data in this year. It is expected that at least some of the methods you use will relate to the spatial dimensions of the data. Your report should include a brief introduction including relevant contextual information at the beginning and a critical review of your findings at the end. You must include at least one map.

Data

  • List of evictions - https://data.cityofnewyork.us/City-Government/Evictions/6z8x-wfk4
  • New York City community districts - https://data.cityofnewyork.us/City-Government/Community-Districts/yfnk-k7r4

Initial project scope

Background and Context

The evictions are frequently triggered by financial hardship or systemic inequalities, disproportionately affecting vulnerable populations. The consequences of evictions extend far beyond the immediate loss of housing, potentially challenges including homelessness and long-term economic instability. Given these implications, understanding eviction spatial and temporal patterns becomes paramount for developing informed policy-making strategies and implementing effective tenant protection measures.

Research question and aim

  • Research question: Do evictions occur in specific community districts, and are they more likely to happen in commercial or residential properties?
  • Primary aim: Analyze eviction spatial patterns in NYC whether evictions exhibit significant spatial clustering or distinctive geographical characteristics focus on 2020 data
  • Specific objectives:
    1. Examine temporal trends from 2017-2024 to contextualize 2020 data (line chart)
    2. Analyze spatial distribution of evictions across NYC community districts (kernel density map or choropleth map)
    3. Compare commercial versus residential eviction patterns (bar chart & map by borough)
    4. Identify potential eviction wether they have spatial clustering or not (DBSCAN)

Data and Methodology

Data Sources

  • NYC Eviction Records (2017-2024)
    • Key variables: execution dates, locations, Residential.Commercial
    • Initial data quality assessment needed for missing values (latitude and longitude)
  • NYC Community Districts boundaries
    • Administrative boundaries for spatial analysis

Analysis Steps

  1. Data Quality Assessment
    • Evaluate completeness of spatial coordinates and other key variables
    • Handle missing values appropriately
  2. Temporal Analysis
    • Create monthly and annual line charts (2017-2024)
    • Position 2020 data within broader temporal context
  3. Spatial Analysis
    • Generate point-based eviction maps
    • Create choropleth maps by community district
  4. Property Type Analysis
    • Compare commercial and residential eviction percentages by borough (bar chart, map)
  5. Advanced Spatial Analysis
    • Apply DBSCAN clustering to identify most serious areas of evictions

Limitations and Constraints

  • Focus on 2020 may reflect unusual patterns due to COVID-19
  • Variable constraints(income, race, etc.) may limit advanced statistical analyses

plot monthly eviction counts from 2017 to 2024
evictions$YearMonth <- as.Date(paste0(format(as.Date(evictions$Executed.Date), "%Y-%m"), "-01"))

monthly_counts <- evictions %>%
  group_by(YearMonth) %>%
  summarise(Count = n(), .groups = 'drop')

ggplot(monthly_counts, aes(x = YearMonth, y = Count, group = 1)) +
  geom_line(size = 1.5, color = "#5e5eff") + 
  labs(title = "Monthly Eviction Counts from 2017 to 2024",
       x = "Year and Month",  
       y = "Count of Court Index Numbers") + 
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

- The line and bar charts reveal significantly lower eviction numbers during 2020-2021 (COVID-19 period) compared to other years in our dataset. This notable decline suggests that 2020 may not be representative of typical eviction patterns, likely due to pandemic-related eviction moratoriums and other emergency housing policies. Therefore, we should exercise caution when interpreting this period’s data as it may not reflect normal eviction trends in New York City.

plot 2020 evictions by property type
# select 2020 data to analysis
evictions_2020 <- evictions[format(as.Date(evictions$Executed.Date), "%Y") == "2020", ]
evictions_2020_sf <- evictions_2020 %>%
  filter(!is.na(Latitude) & !is.na(Longitude)) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("Longitude", "Latitude"), 
           crs = 4326)
tm_shape(districts) +

- The map “NYC Evictions in 2020” highlights eviction events across New York City, categorized as Commercial (red) and Residential (orange). Evictions are concentrated in areas like Brooklyn, Bronx and Manhattan, with fewer cases in Staten Island and Queens. Commercial evictions are more prevalent in central business districts like Manhattan, while residential evictions are widespread, particularly in Brooklyn and the Bronx.

plot 2020 evictions by kernal density
evictions_2020_projected <- st_transform(evictions_2020_sf, 32118) #New York State Plane East (meters)
districts_projected <- st_transform(districts, 32118)
gradient_color <- colorRampPalette(c("#ffffff", "#FEC44F", "#ff6600"))(5) 


win <- as.owin(st_bbox(districts_projected))

# kernal density
pts <- st_coordinates(evictions_2020_projected)
ppp_obj <- ppp(pts[,1], pts[,2], window = win)
## Warning: data contain duplicated points
kde <- density.ppp(ppp_obj, 
                  sigma = 2000, # adjust smooth parameter
                  eps = c(100, 100)) # grid size

# convert to raster data
r <- raster(as.im(kde))
crs(r) <- st_crs(districts_projected)$wkt

# plot density map
tm_shape(districts_projected) +
  tm_borders(col = "#000000") +
  tm_shape(r) +
  tm_raster(palette = gradient_color,
            title = "Eviction Density",
            alpha = 0.7,
            style = "fisher") +
  tm_layout(title = "NYC Evictions in 2020(Kernal Density)",
            title.size = 1.2,
            frame = FALSE) +
  tm_shape(districts_projected) +
  tm_borders(col = "#2c2c2c", lwd = 1)

- The kernal density map provides a more detailed view of eviction density across NYC community districts. The highest eviction density is concentrated in Bronx area. These regions show the darkest orange shades, indicating significant housing pressures and the most frequent eviction cases in 2020.

plot 2020 evictions by DBSCAN
#
coords <- st_coordinates(evictions_2020_projected)

dbscan_result <- dbscan(coords, 
                       eps = 300, # search radius (meters)
                       MinPts = 5) # minimum points to form a cluster

# add cluster result to the original data
evictions_2020_clustered <- evictions_2020_projected %>%
  mutate(cluster = factor(dbscan_result$cluster))

# plot cluster map
tm_shape(districts_projected) +
  tm_polygons(col = "#f0f0f0", 
              alpha = 0.5,
              border.col = "white") +
  tm_shape(evictions_2020_clustered %>% 
           filter(cluster != 0)) + #filter cluster = 0
  tm_dots(col = "cluster",
          palette = "Accent",
          size = 0.1,
          title = "Cluster ID") +
  tm_layout(title = "Eviction Clusters in NYC (2020)",
           title.size = 1.2,
           frame = FALSE,
           legend.outside = TRUE)+
  tm_shape(districts_projected) +
  tm_borders(col = "#2c2c2c", lwd = 1)
## Warning: Number of levels of the variable "cluster" is 121, which is larger
## than max.categories (which is 30), so levels are combined. Set
## tmap_options(max.categories = 121) in the layer function to show all levels.

# calculate the number of each cluster
cluster_summary <- evictions_2020_clustered %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  group_by(cluster) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  filter(cluster != 0) %>% # exclude noise points
  arrange(desc(count))

print(cluster_summary)

  • there are more than 100 clusters, so I only show the top 10 clusters
top_10_clusters <- cluster_summary %>%
  head(10) %>%
  pull(cluster)

evictions_2020_top10 <- evictions_2020_clustered %>%
  filter(cluster %in% top_10_clusters) %>%
  mutate(cluster = factor(cluster, levels = top_10_clusters))

tm_shape(districts_projected) +
  tm_polygons(col = "#f0f0f0", 
              alpha = 0.5,
              border.col = "white") +

Conclusion

  • The analysis reveals that evictions are not evenly distributed across NYC community districts, with higher concentrations in certain areas. Commercial evictions are more prevalent in Manhattan, while residential evictions are widespread, particularly in Brooklyn and the Bronx. The kernal density map and DBSCAN clustering analysis provide a more detailed view of eviction density and clustering patterns, highlighting areas of concentrated housing instability. The NYC government should focus on the areas with high eviction density and clustering patterns to implement effective tenant protection measures.

limitations

  • The analysis is limited to 2020 data, which may not fully represent the typical eviction patterns in NYC.
  • According to the annual eviction counts, the eviction rate continues to increase after 2021, which might change the eviction patterns.
  • The analysis does not consider other factors that may influence eviction rates, such as income, race, and housing affordability.
